						               													<description>Avalanche Press calls this their &amp;quot;Ultimate World War II Naval Game&amp;quot; - a claim with some merit, it would seem, as this game is ENORMOUS.  &amp;ldquo;Leyte Gulf&amp;rdquo; is a &amp;quot;Second World War at Sea&amp;quot;-series game based on the final struggles of the Imperial Japanese Navy. The largest naval battles in history are included here &amp;ndash; the Battle of Leyte Gulf and the Battle of the Philippine Sea.  In addition, the Battles of Cape Enga&amp;ntilde;o, Surigao Strait, and Okinawa are covered by the game.  The American fleet is enormous in this product, while the whittled-down Japanese fleet is not much larger than the &amp;ldquo;SOPAC&amp;rdquo; and &amp;ldquo;Midway&amp;rdquo; games.  To &amp;lsquo;balance&amp;rsquo; that side in hypothetical scenarios, some projected but never completed, or sometimes built, units are available as options to the Japanese &amp;ndash; such as the third Yamato-class battleship, all six Unryu-class carriers, the &amp;ldquo;B64&amp;rdquo;-type Battlecruiser (one of the two named by AP &amp;ldquo;Sagami&amp;rdquo;), as well as squadrons of hypothetical &amp;ldquo;second generation&amp;rdquo; Japanese aircraft.  It&amp;rsquo;s a &amp;ldquo;worst case scenario&amp;rdquo; plan for American military staff.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The Americans get some new toys, too, including the first appearance in the series of the F4U Corsair, the Iowa-class battleships (and a special guest appearance by the Montana-class), Baltimore-class heavy cruisers, Cleveland-class light cruisers, Independence-class escort carriers, Essex-class fleet carriers, and the fabulous Alaska-class battlecruisers...errr...&amp;rdquo;large cruisers&amp;rdquo;, that is.&amp;#10;The Royal Navy, Australian Navy, and New Zealand Navy all make appearances as well, driving this product up to simply ludicrous counter numbers!&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Leyte Gulf includes: &amp;#10;&amp;#10;     24&amp;rdquo;x18&amp;rdquo; tactical map &amp;#10;     Three 34&amp;rdquo;x22&amp;rdquo; operational maps &amp;#10;     Nearly 2,000 game pieces &amp;#10;     24-page series rule book &amp;#10;     24-page scenario book &amp;#10;     2-player aid cards &amp;#10;     6-organizational cards&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
